 <div class="hobbytipsheading"><h3 class="heading"> The Wet Palette!</h3></div>
 <div class="articleintro"><div class="introwords"><p class="tipheading">By Jamie Vaughan - 26th March 2021</p><p>I am no expert, but over the last 3 years I have become a little bit obsessed with painting and modelling miniatures. Its not 100% the same as scale modelling real world planes trains and auto-mobiles, but our camps are settled not so far apart. I feel I’ve advanced a lot in this short time and thought, if I were to pass on some advice, what would I say? Well here it is, my humble advice in a nutshell, some pointers that may expand your horizons as a scale model enthusiast! </p></div><div class="picboxright"><span class="authorborder"><img src="images/wraithblades.jpg" class="authorpic cubbyimg" title="Wraithblades" alt="Wraithblades"></span><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Some of my Aedari army - Wraithblades</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/wetpalette.jpg" title="wet palette" alt="wet palette"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">A wet palette. Its been well used.</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p> Today's Topic: The Wet Palette.<br><br>
 &nbsp;&nbsp;To understand a wet palette, you first need to have struggled with a dry one. The paint dries out fast, is hard to maintain a moisture level that suits the paint and worst of all, it’s wasteful. When you’ve painted 100 Space Marines in a row, the same problems crop up, my paint is dry again. So you’re conscious of time ticking away before you need fresh paint again. We don’t need that stress! 
 </p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Enter the wet palette. Used right, solves these issues. It also offers a unique situation, where the custom colour you’ve just created is now usable a month later! (I’ve even heard tales of years later, but I can’t vouch for quality of the paint by then) I love the fact this takes the pressure off, and it speeds things up. Techniques like wet blending become much more feasible. My favourite part about using a wet palette, is when I feel like doing some painting, I can be set up, correct colours at hand, within seconds. That hesitation to continue painting is wonderfully diminished. </p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/captaincape.jpg" title="A wet blended Cloak" alt="A wet blended Cloak"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">My attempt at wet blending, made much easier with a wet palette.</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><a href="https://www.bulldogmodels.co.uk/products/acrylic-wet-pallet?_pos=1&_sid=602e09b2e&_ss=r&variant=41508943167641" target="_blank"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/bulldogpalette1.jpg" title="Click to go to product - Bulldog Models Wet palette" alt="Bulldog Models Wet palette link"></a><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Our friends at Bulldog Models do a rather nice palette. Click to visit!</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>If I’ve not sold it to you yet, there is a financial incentive too. You could buy a model shop set up for a wet palette. It’ll usually cost about £15, often with sponge and paper included, and these work great. Or you can try the DIY option of a shallow, Tupperware pot (with airtight lid), a kitchen flannel and some baking paper cut to size. This will barely cost you any coins at all and you will be stocked for years. The cost of either option will be mitigated in no time at all as you will be using a fraction of the paint used previously on a dry palette.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Correct use of a wet palette is needed. Keep the amount of moisture in the pot balanced. Water should only just be visible when you roll the palette about a bit. Too much and the top surface floods and contaminates the rest of the palette. Too little and you’re back to using a dry palette. Its not a difficult balance to find though. Also try to identify your baking papers waxy side and use that as the top surface. When mixing your paint, your brush will rub the surface and may rough up the baking paper, and in turn add fibres to your paint. Waxy side up will limit this.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/palettematerials.jpg" title="wet palette materials" alt="wet palette materials"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">These days, I cut a bunch of replacements to size in advance.</p>
 </div></div></div>
 <div class="conclusion"><p>Have any pointers to add to this article? Send us a message on the contact us button, we’d be only too happy to hear your perspective!</p></div>
</div>
                                 
