 <div class="hobbytipsheading"><h3 class="heading"> Paint Brush Care</h3></div>
 <div class="articleintro"><div class="introwords"><p class="tipheading">By Jamie Vaughan - 15th April 2021</p><p>I’ve been using paint brushes for a long time without having a clue about them. You might think for a professional artist with a degree in Painting and Printmaking, and well over 20 years of painting experience, I might have known a thing or two about the tools of my trade. However, having reapplied myself to learning how to paint miniatures, I have found a number of techniques that really help with brush care. Okay so I didn’t grow up with the internet, not a lot of us did I’d imagine! So what have I found out since then? What was I getting so wrong.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><span class="authorborder"><img src="images/jamievaughan.jpg" class="authorpic cubbyimg" title="artist Jamie Vaughan at work" alt="artist Jamie Vaughan at work"></span><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Mixed Media Artist, Jamie Vaughan - that's me in my workshop</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/badbrushcare.jpg" title="Some poorly cared for Brushes" alt="Some poorly cared for Brushes"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Oh my poor brushes - examples of how not to treat your brushes</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>My brush care was atrocious. I’d leave brushes sat in dirty water for days. Paint would cover the brush head to toe. Once finished with, I’d not clean the brush properly. It embarrasses me to think what little care I took. And so I was going through brushes at an appalling rate. The handle would split and the coat would flake off. The bristles would splay open, uncontrollable. Masking tape used to hold the brush together would get soaked and fall off in bits. I’d wrongly blame these cheap, hand-me-down brushes, and assume that the reason for my issues was that I didn’t have the money for decent brushes.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>I’ve also heard a lot of talk of the differences between synthetic and natural sable bristles, which I’m not going to go into detail in this article. That using natural sable bristles are superior, and yet also stories of chemical cleaners or water that’s too hot weakening some brushes. Well of course it depends entirely on what paint you’re using the brush with, and what you’re cleaning the brush with after. For the purposes of this article I will be talking about using brushes with acrylic paint, but some advice will certainly cross over to other mediums.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/paintbrush.jpg" title="Variety of brushes" alt="Variety of brushes"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Used, but cared for brushes</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/ferrule.jpg" title="the ferrule is the metal collar where the bristles are mounted" alt="the ferrule is the metal collar where the bristles are mounted"><div class="central"><p class="picheading"></p>The ferrule is the metal collar where the bristles are mounted</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>Keep your ferrule clean! This is the metal casing around the bristles. If any paint is allowed to dry inside there, it will harden, and separate the bristles. That’s right, it wasn’t the cheap-o brush’s fault, it was you all along! This can be remedied later on, but the best cure is prevention. Don’t dip your brush deep into the paint, only allow the tip of the brush to touch the paint and you won’t have this problem in the first place. If you’ve allowed paint in there by accident, clean it immediately. If the paint dries, things get more difficult to clean but not impossible. A soak in an appropriate paint cleaner, then gently easing out the paint onto a clean cloth can recover your brush. But the more paint stuck in there, the more bristles you’re going to inadvertently pull out. </p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>When you’ve finished with a brush, clean it immediately. A simple discipline. Don’t leave it sitting in your water (or your ‘not drink’ mug). Yes the paint wont dry on it like that, but you’re training the bristols to bend to one side, and that’s no good. Keep your brush clean and straight. Let it dry shaped to a point and store it tip upward. Maybe even use those little plastic sleeves it came with. If you know where that went, I’ve no idea as to the location of mine though. Also worth keeping 2 water jars for cleaning, saving one for metallic based paints. This will prevents unwanted sparkles. Change your water frequently too. </p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/waterpots.jpg" title="Water Pots" alt="Water Pots"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">'M' for cleaning metal paint!</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/drybrush.jpg" title="A make up brush that's good for drybrushing" alt="A make up brush that's good for drybrushing"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">A make up brush that's great for drybrushing bigger builds, like scener</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>Save certain brushes for certain jobs. Your best, grade ‘A’, brush should be spared from the heavy lifting. That fine point is your greatest ally! Avoid using it with metallic paints. Avoid using it with ink washes that will get in the ferrule. In fact your pretty much only going to use it for those fine finishing details and mid to upper layers of acrylic paint. Base coating should be completed using a larger, less refined brush. If you’re a dry-brusher, expect this technique to either destroy your brush in short time, or switch to a make up blusher brush. Don’t be embarrassed, head down to your local make up supplier.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>After some use, even with great care,  your ferrule is still going to fill up with paint particles. After spending some time repeatedly discussing which chemical to clean acrylic paint with, there has been, in my mind, one winner over all. Isopropanol, also known as Isopropyl Alcohol. This stuff is dangerous. Its near 100% alcohol. Using it in confined spaces with no respirator is going to get you drunk in a bad way. It’ll damage your lungs, and if it goes anywhere near a flame, say goodbye to your eyebrows. Some professional outlets, like watch repair shops, will only ration out very small amounts for use during watch cleaning due to its volatile nature. And absolutely do not use it in combination with an ultrasonic cleaner! (Flammable liquid and electrical devices don’t mix!).</p> </div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/isopropanol.jpg" style="max-height: 100%" title="Isopropanol or Isopropyl Alcohol" alt="Isopropanol or Isopropyl Alcohol"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Here it is, the mega stuff that will clean most things. Handle with care!</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Having said all of this, Isopropanol will strip acrylic paint. Many a discussion as to cleaning products from the antiseptic cleaner ‘Dettol’, to the Americans ‘Simple Green’, has been had by many miniature painters out there (its almost a repeated weekly discussion on one group I am part of), but the active ingredient that is doing the heavy work is Isoproponol. Get yourself on Ebay, and order a litre of the stuff. Madly, they will post this to you in the UK, no fuss! I bet you never knew being a postal worker was potentially such a dangerous job!</p></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/soap.jpg" title="brush soap" alt="brush soap"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">This is as exciting as it gets - Brush Soap!</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>Once your brush has been cleaned or restored, it may still be a bit frizzy. Time for brush conditioner. There are a few sources online that suggest using hair conditioner or clothes conditioner. There are also dedicated paint brush conditioner soaps out there as well. It might seem like a bit of over-care, but once you’ve bitten the bullet and purchased that highly recommended sable brush, it would be prudent to make it last as long as you can.</p></div></div>
 <div class="conclusion"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Once again, I point out, we thrive on your input! Anything to add or questions to ask, please drop us a message on the contact button, and we shall look to include it these articles!</p></div></div>
</div>
   
