 <div class="hobbytipsheading"><h3 class="heading"> Scenery Building</h3></div>
 <div class="articleintro"><div class="introwords"><p class="tipheading">By Jamie Vaughan - 1st June 2021</p><p>I recently came into possession of a martian landscape battle mat. It is a photo realistic, 6'x 4' mouse mat for playing Warhammer 40k on, and I love it. However, it made my scenery for the game look rather poor! So I decided to create a batch of scenery to match it! Here is my little journey of production.</p></div><div class="picboxright largerpic"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/scenery and mat.jpg" title="scenery and mat" alt="scenery and mat"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">The finished effect, matching the mat.</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/plastic scenery.jpg" title="Plastic Scenery" alt="Plastic Scenery"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Some plastic, preformed scenery from Games Workshop</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>Here is the Plastic scenery I had previously purchased and assembled. It's a far cry from the cardboard houses I would build as a kid! Some of the details and styles on these models would be hard to replicate, but not impossible, but my priority has always been building the models, these are just meant to be background scenery.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>As ever with any painting on plastic, it needed priming. I used Vallejo's grey primer. There is apparently better out there but I have a bottle to get through first. I needed to sieve the paint before putting it in the airbrush, as the paint had gone lumpy, even after a thorough shake. Might be because my shed's outdoors and has endured a winter or two? I don't know.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/primed plastic.jpg" title="primed plastic" alt="primed plastic"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">My little spray booth. It's in my shed and I wear a good mask for safety</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/black basecoat.jpg" title="black basecoat" alt="black basecoat"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Vallejo's Nato Black for a basecoat</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>I then gave it all a basecoat of Vallejo's Nato black. It's not a true black, It's actually a very very very dark grey (Father Ted reference anyone?). It gives a lovely matt finish that gives even blacker blacks somewhere to go, while allowing other paints to adhere to it beautifully.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Next was a dry brush of a metallic paint, in this case I used Citadel's Leadbelcher Air paint (because it was already on my shelf) If I wanted I could stop here as this produces an amazing effect, but I'm going further with this. I used a large make up brush to apply this and it did its job quickly and cleanly.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/metal drybrushed.jpg" title="metal drybrushed" alt="metal drybrushed"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Metallic paint Drybrushed on</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/copper added.jpg" title="copper added" alt="copper added"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">A metallic copper paint is added to highlight a few details</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>I didn't want to go mad detailing these pieces, but a few additions can go a long way. The colour needed to be very strong for the next stage to take effect correctly, so I had to be patient and stick to the plan!</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>Next I switched to to an enamel paint, AK Interactives Rust Streaks. Its talent in a tin as far as I'm concerned. There will be other brands out there but this one works. You can spray this fairly liberally, but I added extra to the lower half to give the impression of dust concentrations. It's benefit of being an enamel is that it takes a long time to dry. So theres no hurry, but I had to be careful handling the pieces afterwards.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/rust added.jpg" title="rust added" alt="rust added"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Enamel paint, AK Interactives Rust Streaks.</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/remove rust.jpg" title="remove rust" alt="remove rust"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Cleaning off the excess rust.</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p> Next stage was to clean off the excess rust. I used biodegradable cottonbuds (because what else are they for?!). Often I've seen oil and enamel miniature painters using these with alcohol to clean off paints, but with this enamal paint, it isn't needed. Wherever upper highlights needed to be retained, I cleaned off the edges of the models. It took a few days to properly dry after this.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>In this next image, I've skipped ahead because I didn't technically do this until later on. But I have added Revell's weathering powders kit rather heavily to the bases of the pieces to simulate red Martian dust gathering at the base (I know, I know, Mars isn't really that red!). Also added Nikalah Oxide from Citadel to give the copper an older, more realistic rusted look.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/weathering and verdigris.jpg" title="weathering and verdigris" alt="weathering and verdigris"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">I added some weathering dust to the base and verdigris to the copper.</p></div></div></div> <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/sand and stones drying.jpg" title="sand and stones drying" alt="sand and stones drying"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">It was a sunny day, and the sand and stones needed drying out first.</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>Ok, so, onto the bases for these pieces and a few other pieces of scenery I had in mind. I needed to make the texture somewhat rocky and sandy, so what better way to simulate that, than actual rocks and sand! In an ideal world I'd have used a variety of sizes of sand to get the scale looking right, but I had some sand left over from some building work, so I was happy enough using that for now.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>I needed some bases cut next. I had a tonne of MDF knocking about so I used that. It's not ideal , but if it's prepared correctly it will do. I used a vertical fret saw to cut these out but a hand fret saw would do the job just fine. Just a hell of a lot quicker with the right tools!</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/wood cut.jpg" title="wood cut" alt="wood cut"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">MDF bases cut using a Vertical Fret Saw.</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/wood primed.jpg" title="wood primed" alt="wood primed"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">The MDF has been carefully primed here.</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>As just mentioned, MDF is not ideal for bases, as the slightest bit of water will warp and enlarge it. And we're using paint here... So I primed the bases very sparingly all over the surface and edges, let it dry, then repeated. Important to not warp the MDF with the layer thats supposed to protect it! As it turned out, this did an excellent job protecting the wood from warpage.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p> I've a fair amount of experience with using tiling grout, and I'd noticed that in large enough amounts, it cracks all over the place. That's what I want my craters to look like! Being careful not to add too much water, I mixed up some tiler's finishing grout into an almost clay like consistancy. I was then able to shape it onto the base and make a crater shape.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/craters shaped.jpg" title="craters shaped" alt="craters shaped"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Tiling grout used as modelling clay.</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/glue on sand.jpg" title="glue on sand" alt="glue on sand"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Sand was glued on liberally</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>I glued on  some printed paper scenery that came with my miniatures and glued the pieces to their bases. I wanted to make all the surface areas have texture now, so I glued on big rocks, little rocks and then added a layer of sand to all the bases. It was easiest to put the sand in a pot and dip the glued pieces in one at a time. I then left the glue to dry over night.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>I base coated everything a dark brown red colour, using fairly basic acrylic paint (not the good stuff for your models!). Then took a large brush and dabbed on a middle reddy orange. Once that was dry I made up a mix of black and brown acrylic paint, mixed it with a bit of alcohol to break it down, then added a fair bit of water. This created a wash that could seep into all the deepest parts and give it depth. I added a bit at the bottom of the structures as well.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/ready for dust.jpg" title="ready for dust" alt="ready for dust"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Base coated and ready for the final layer of 'dust'</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/weathering dust.jpg" title="weathering dust" alt="weathering dust"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Weathering dust like these are great tools!</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>I had to experiment a bit here. I got out my old pastels and scrapped off all sorts of tones and colours, constantly referrring to a picture of my mat. It needed a range of browns reds and yellows, but in the end I reverted back to using my Revell's weathering set. My supply took a hammering but I think it was worth it.</p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>After a few layers, going back and forth, I ended up settling with this appearance. I think in future I might add more rocks and debris, but for now it's done! I added a quick layer of cheapo hair spray to seal it in. For a moment it looked too dark but it dried out light again.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/weathered crater.jpg" title="weathered crater" alt="weathered crater"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">The finished weathering effect</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft largerpic"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/scenery/battle scenery.jpg" title="battle scenery" alt="battle scenery"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">I'm pretty stoked by the result!</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>And we're done! I had to set it all up with two of my painted armies to demonstrate the effect, but it really takes my breath away seeing it in person. I think it will always be work in progress but what's been achieved so far hasn't been too taxing. I can't wait to have some battles now!</p></div></div>
</div>
   
