 <div class="hobbytipsheading"><h3 class="heading"> Airfix Model World and IPMS Magazines</h3></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p class="tipheading">By Lee Hayward - 18th January 2022</p>
 <p>Both my monthly subscription magazines have landed in the last two days. Always nice to get the Airfix one, even nicer to see a separate pull out section in this one, featuring the Revell Mandalorian offering of the Razor Crest. The guy who’s reviewed it didn’t get any instructions, decals or anything. Just the kit. </p></div>
 <div class="picboxright"><span class="authorborder"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/Razor Sharp.jpg" title="Razor Sharp" alt="Razor Sharp"></span><div class="central"><p class="picheading">The Mandalorian's Ship</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/Parts Close-up.jpg" title="Parts Close-up" alt="Parts Close-up">
 <div class="central"><p class="picheading">Parts Close-up</p></div></div>
 <div class="sectionwords"><p>He’s made a stunning job of it right down to masking the yellow markings and fully researching the colours of every part. As the kit is half the size of the actual studio piece they used for filming it’s an impressive offering. I can get these kits currently and the RRP is about £50. 
 </p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>The mag, amongst other things, covers the new HK 1/48 Lanc. Another beauty. This is a great magazine and I’m really glad to get it every month.</p></div><div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/Lancaster Bomber.jpg" title="Lancaster Bomber" alt="Lancaster Bomber"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Lancaster Bomber</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/IPMS Magazine.jpg" title="IPMS Magazine" alt="IPMS Magazine"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">IPMS Magazine</p></div></div><div class="sectionwords"><p>The IPMS mag landed. Getting this is almost the same as going to a model club. I get a lot of inspiration from it. I’ve never once regretted joining the IPMS. It’s nice to be part of a larger thing and it’s surprising how global they are and how much IPMS members do to power the hobby forward. </p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>This months mag is pretty much taken over with Scale model world. Nice to see all the SIG’s represented there, but as always since joining I’m enjoying the “lockdown” builds, even if we aren’t currently locked down. One would have thought that when under compulsory lockdown we model makers would have been in our element. Hoarding products is a big part of who we are and we were born for this moment right? I thought I’d hear a deafening clamour as everyone rushed to their benches. Instead, something surprising happened. </p></div>
 <div class="picboxright"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/Model Displays.jpg" title="Model Displays" alt="Model Displays"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Model Displays</p>
 </div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/Lockdown Models.jpg" title="Lockdown Models" alt="Lockdown Models"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">Lockdown Models</p></div></div>
 <div class="sectionwords"><p>Most people will tell you they almost stopped building, or at least their pace dropped off significantly. A lot of us opted for at home bars, learning to cook the food we couldn’t get take away; and paying homage to our expanding waistlines. If anything, it went a long way towards proving that we are, against everything that’s been said about us, very social animals. When the curtain fell, and the chips were laid down, we missed each other; and the energy our meetings and shenanigans provided. We are, despite what the press might say, quite social animals, within our own kind at least. The outside world though? They can still stay at arms length right?  </p></div></div>
