<div class="reveal" id="article5">
 <div class="hobbytipsheading"><h3 class="heading"> Tamiya FRS1 Build</h3></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p class="tipheading">By Lee Hayward - 18th January 2022</p><p>I’ve just finished this gnarly old Tamiya 1/48 FRS1. It wasn’t as bad as people had me believe, especially once realising all that’s needed to make it a not-so horrific build-wise is to fit the engine in, cover it, THEN attach the jet nozzles to the fuselage. </p><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/FRS1 box and instructions.jpg" title="FRS1 box and instructions" alt="FRS1 box and instructions"></div>
 <div class="picboxright"><span class="authorborder"><iframe width="320" height="569" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/R56Z5s1sDFU" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe></span></div></div>
 <div class="section1">
 <div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/FRS1 markings.jpg" title="FRS1 markings" alt="FRS1 markings"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">FRS1 markings</p></div></div>
 <div class="sectionwords"><p>I did an after-market scheme, so this is the XZ457 HMS Hermes. She had all her markings overpainted dark sea grey all over by brush whilst on Hermes and only basic markings re-applied. Each of the markings are well documented for this aircraft. She sports her kill markings. The gun pods were loaned to her by the RAF. </p></div></div>
 <div class="section2"><div class="sectionwords"><p>On 21st of May, following an attack on HMS Ardent, Lieutenant Clive (Spag) Morrel shot down one A-4Q Skyhawk A-307 with a Sidewinder and damaged another with 30mm Cannon fire. </p><p>The second aircraft was subsequently confirmed as a "victory" after the conflict when it was confirmed that the pilot had ejected with undercarriage failure, whilst trying to land at Port Stanley airfield. </p></div>
 <div class="picboxright"><iframe width="320" height="569" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/DpOa_1m9txI" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe><div class="central"><p class="picheading"></p></div></div></div>
 <div class="section1"><div class="picboxleft"><img class="cubbyimg" src="images/FRS1 on holder.jpg" title="FRS1 on holder" alt="FRS1 on holder"><div class="central"><p class="picheading">FRS1 on holder (holder available at Bulldog Models)</p></div></div>
 <div class="sectionwords"><p>On May 24th, Lieutenant-Commander Andy Auld shot down two Group 6 Daggers with Sidewinders over Pebble Island so became the highest scoring Sea harrier during the Falklands conflict.</p><p> On the 20th October 1994 she suffered an uncontainable engine failure during take off and in the subsequent fire suffered extensive damage to the front fuselage, particularly on the starboard side. The Pilot Lieutenant-Commander Bayliss ejected successfully.</p></div></div>
